\section{Mathematical Background}


Our development of the background material on relations, terms, substitutions, and rewrite rules substantially follows that of
\citet{Huet80}, with considerable influence also from 
\citet{van-oostrom:decreasing-diagrams} and \citet{ariola:skew-confluence}.


\subsection{Relations, Terms, and Rewrite Rules}


\subsubsection{Relations}


A \emph{relation} is a set of pairs of related items. We use letters, such as $R$ and $S$, as well as symbols, such as $\subset$ and $\leq$ and $\rightarrow$ and $\equiv$, to name relations.
If $A$ and $B$ are sets, then any $R \subseteq A \times B$ is a \emph{relation from $A$ to $B$}; if $A=B$, so that $R \subseteq A \times A$,
then $R$ is a \emph{relation on $A$}.

Any relation, regarded as a set, may be used as the operand of operators such as $\cup$ and $\cap$ and of predicates such as $\subseteq$ and $\in$.
Any relation may also be regarded as a binary predicate; if $R$ is a relation, then $x \mathrel{R} y$ means $(x,y)\in R$.
Because letters and symbols alike may be used to name relations,
we can also say that if $\rightarrow$ is a relation, then $x \mathrel{\rightarrow} y$ means $(x, y)\in {\rightarrow}$.
If $R$ and $S$ are relations, then $R \cap S$ is the set $\setcomp{(x, y)}{(x,y) \in R \logand (x,y) \in S}$ = $\setcomp{(x, y)}{x \mathrel{R} y \logand x \mathrel{S} y}$,
and one can write $a \mathrel{(R\cap S)} b$, which will true if and only if $a \mathrel{R} s \logand a \mathrel{S} b$.
As another example, if $\leftarrow$ and $\rightarrow$ are relations,
then ${\leftarrow}\cup{\rightarrow}$ is the set $\setcomp{(x, y)}{(x,y) \in {\leftarrow} \logand (x,y) \in {\rightarrow}}$ = $\setcomp{(x, y)}{x \leftarrow y \logand x \rightarrow y}$,
and one can write $a \mathrel{({\leftarrow}\cup {\rightarrow})} b$, which will true if and only if $a \leftarrow b \logor a \rightarrow b$.

We use the customary notation for \emph{conjunctive chaining} of relation predicates, so that for any $n>0$, $x_0 \mathrel{R_1} x_1 \mathrel{R_2}  x_2 \mathrel{R_3} \cdots \mathrel{R_n} x_n$
means $x_0 \mathrel{R_1} x_1 \logand x_1 \mathrel{R_2} x_2 \logand x_2 \mathrel{R_3} x_3 \logand \cdots \logand x_{n-1} \mathrel{R_n} x_n$.
For example, $x \leq y \leq z$ means $x \leq y \logand y \leq z$.


We write $\iota_A$ for the identity relation on $A$: $\iota_A = \setcomp{(x,x)}{x \in A}$.
The operator $\relcomp$ is \emph{relation composition}: if $R$ and $S$ are relations, then $R \relcomp S$ means $\setcomp{(x, y)}{\exists z \suchthat x \mathrel{R} z \mathrel{S} y}$.
A nonnegative integer superscript $k$ may used to indicate $k$-fold composition of a relation; if $R$ and $\xgo{}$ are relations on $A$, then $R^0 = {\xgosup{}{0}} = \iota_A$,
and for $k>0$, $R^{k} = R \relcomp R^{k-1}$ and ${\xgosup{}{k}} = {\xgo{}} \relcomp {\xgosup{}{k-1}}$.


The \emph{inverse} of a relation $R$ is the set $R^{-1} = \setcomp{(x,y)}{(y,x) \in R}$; note that $(R^{-1})^{-1}=R$.
While the superscript $^{-1}$ could be applied to symbols as well as letters, we instead customarily notate the inverse of a relation
that is named by a symbol by flipping the symbol left-to-right, so that $\supset$ denotes the inverse of $\subset$, $\geq$ denotes the inverse of $\leq$,
and $\leftarrow$ denotes the inverse of $\rightarrow$. This convention implies that, for example, $|e_1| \leftarrow |e| \rightarrow |e_2|$, which abbreviates
$|e_1| \leftarrow |e| \logand |e| \rightarrow |e_2|$, means the same as $|e| \rightarrow |e_1| \logand |e| \rightarrow |e_2|$.


A relation $R$ is said to be \emph{symmetric} if $R^{-1}=R$. It is customary to use symbols that are left-right symmetric, such as $\equiv$ and $\leftrightarrow$ and $\Leftrightarrow$, to denote symmetric relations.

Arrows have different \emph{styles} if they have different shafts or different subscripts. For example, $\leftrightarrow$ and $\Leftrightarrow$ and $\xpgo{}$ have different styles, because their shafts are all different; $\xgo{}$ and $\xrngo{r}$ and $\xgo{\rr}$ and $\xrngo{subst}$ have different styles because their subscripts (or lack of subscript) are all different.
But $\leftarrow$ and $\rightarrow$ and $\leftrightarrow$and $\uparrow$and $\downarrow$ all have the same style,
and $\xrngo{r}$ and $\xrngodbl{r}$ and $\xrnungo{r}$ and $\xrnungodbl{r}$ all have the same style.

Again, let $R$ and $\xgo{}$ be relations on $A$.
We use a superscripted $\reflexivemarker$ on a relation to indicate its reflexive closure; thus
the reflexive closure of $R$ is $R^{\reflexivemarker}=R \cup \iota_A$ and the reflexive closure of $\xgo{}$ is ${\xgoeq{}} = {\xgo{}} \cup \iota_A$.
We use a superscripted $*$ on a relation to indicate the transitive reflexive closure, except that if the symbol for a relation is an arrow, then
we use a double-headed arrow of the same style to indicate the transitive reflexive closure; thus
the transitive reflexive closure of $R$ is $R^{*}= \bigcup_{k \geq 0} R^k$ and the transitive reflexive closure of $\xgo{}$ is ${\xgodbl{}} = \bigcup_{k \geq 0} \xgosup{}{k}$.
If the symbol for a relation is a leftward-pointing or rightward-pointing arrow, then
we use a leftward-and-rightward-pointing arrow of the same style to indicate the symmetric closure; thus
the symmetric closure of $\xgo{}$ is ${\xboth{}} = {\xungo{}} \cup {\xgo{}}$, and
the symmetric transitive reflexive closure of $\xgo{}$ is ${\xbothdbl{}} = {\xungodbl{}} \cup {\xgodbl{}}$. 

For a given relation denoted by a rightward arrow $\xgo{}$, we use a downward-pointing arrow of the same style to define the predicate $x \bothreduceto y$ to mean $\exists z \suchthat x \xgodbl{} z \xungodbl{} y$
and we use an upward-pointing arrow of the same style to define the predicate $x \bothreducefrom y$ to mean $\exists z \suchthat x \xungodbl{} z \xgodbl{} y$.

\subsubsection{Metavariables, Terms, and BNF}

We use certain symbols as \emph{metavariables}; the appearance of a metavariable is an abstract stand-in for any of a number of concrete possibilities.
As is customary, we shall use $i$, $j$, $k$, $m$, and $n$ as \emph{integer metavariables}. 

Any symbol that can be used as a metavariable may be \emph{decorated} with a prime mark ${}'$ or integer subscripts to produce a new metavariable having
the same range of possibilities.
An integer subscript may in turn be denoted by an integer metavariable or an arithmetic expression in integer metavariables.

Let {\termvars} be a denumerable set of \emph{term variables}. In this paper, for term variables we shall use lowercase italic letters
other than $i$, $j$, $k$, $m$, and $n$, and occasionally strings of lowercase italic letters (such as |hnf|), all possibly decorated.
We will use the lowercase Greek letters $\xi$ and $\zeta$ as metavariables ranging over term variables.

Let {\functionsyms} be a finite or denumerable set of \emph{function symbols} that are graded by an \emph{arity} function $a: \functionsyms \mathrel{\rightarrow} \mathbb{N}$,
such that $\functionsyms \cap \termvars = \emptyset$. We use uppercase letters $F$, $G$, $H$ as metavariables ranging over function symbols.
For every $n\geq 0$, we define $\functionsyms_n=\setcomp{F}{F \in \functionsyms \logand a(F)=n}$, the set of function symbols of arity $n$.

The set $\termset$ of \emph{terms} is defined to be the free $a$-graded $\functionsyms$-algebra generated by $\termvars$; that is,
every term either is a term variable (an element of $\termvars$) or is, for some $n \geq 0$, of the form $F M_1 M_2\cdots M_n$,
where $F\in\functionsyms_n$ and $M_k\in\termvars$ for all $k$ such that $1\leq k\leq n$.
We use uppercase letters $M$, $N$, $P$, $Q$ as metavariables ranging over terms.

We identify parse trees generated by a BNF grammar with terms in the following manner.
Every BNF nonterminal is a term variable. For any alternative on the right-hand side of a BNF rule,
we may write it within the special brackets $\bnffnsym{\cdots}$, replacing every nonterminal within
that alternative with the placeholder symbol $\bnfhole$, and treat the result as a function symbol;
the arity of this function symbol is the number of occurrences of $\bnfhole$.
Every subtree in the parse tree rooted at a tree node generated from a given BNF alternative corresponds to a term
in which the function symbol is the one derived from that BNF alternative
and each subterm is, or has been generated from, the corresponding BNF nonterminal
within that BNF alternative.

For example, one alternative in the rule for expressions |e| in the Verse Calculus is |fail|;
therefore \bnffnsym{|fail|} is a function symbol of arity 0.
Another alternative is |eq; e|; therefore \bnffnsym{|bnfhole; bnfhole|} is a function symbol of arity 2.
The (incompletely expanded) {\versecalc} expression |x=0; y=3; e| corresponds to the term
$\bnffnsym{|bnfhole; bnfhole|}\bnffnsym{|bnfhole=bnfhole|}\bnfmetavar{|x|}\bnffnsym{0}\bnffnsym{|bnfhole; bnfhole|}\bnffnsym{|bnfhole=bnfhole|}\bnfmetavar{|y|}\bnffnsym{3}\bnfmetavar{|e|}$
because its parse tree looks like this:

\begin{center}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\node{\bnffnsym{|bnfhole; bnfhole|}}
   child {node {\bnffnsym{|bnfhole=bnfhole|}}
      child { node {|x|}}
      child { node {\bnffnsym{0}}}
    }
   child [missing] {}
   child {node {\bnffnsym{|bnfhole; bnfhole|}}
      child {node {\bnffnsym{|bnfhole=bnfhole|}}
         child { node {|y|}}
         child { node {\bnffnsym{3}}}
      }
      child {node {|e|}}
   }
;   
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{center}

One of the alternatives for |hnf| in the Verse Calculus is |tup (v_1, xdots, v_n)|; we regard this as shorthand
for the denumerable set of alternatives |tup ()|, |tup (v_1)|, |tup (v_1, v_2)|,  |tup (v_1, v_2, v_3)|, \ldots, which correspond
to separate function symbols \bnffnsym{|tup ()|}, \bnffnsym{|tup (bnfhole)|}, \bnffnsym{|tup (bnfhole, bnfhole)|},  \bnffnsym{|tup (bnfhole, bnfhole, bnfhole)|}, \ldots,
one for every possible tuple length $n$.

It is possible, and useful, for the same function symbol to be derived from different BNF alternatives.
For example, in {\versecalc}, one alternative for an expression $e$ is |def x e|, which corresponds to the term $\bnffnsym{|def bnfhole bnfhole|}\bnfmetavar{|x|}\bnfmetavar{|e|}$,
and one alternative for a choice context $CX$ is |def x CX|, which corresponds to the term $\bnffnsym{|def bnfhole bnfhole|}\bnfmetavar{|x|}\bnfmetavar{|CX|}$; these terms
contain the same function symbol $\bnffnsym{|def bnfhole bnfhole|}$.

Henceforth we will freely write language expressions where terms might be expected, with the understanding that we mean the term derived by this correspondence
from the parse tree for the expression.

\subsubsection{Occurrences}
We use elements of $\mathbb{N}_{+}^{*}$ (that is, tuples of any finite nonnegative length with elements that are positive integers) to represent the positions of the subterms of a term.
Following \cite[Section 3.1]{Huet80}, we call such tuples \emph{occurrences}; we use variables $u$, $w$, $p$, and $q$ to refer to occurrences,
and we use variables $U$, $W$, $P$, and $Q$ to refer to sets of occurrences.
We use juxtaposition to concatenate such tuples; for example, if $u=(1,2)$ and $w=(2,1,3)$, then $uw =(1,2,2,1,3)$ and $w(2,2)u = (2,1,3,2,2,1,2)$.
Furthermore we sometimes use juxtaposition to concatenate a tuple with every member of a set of tuples to form a new set of tuples;
for example, if $U=\{(1,2),(2,1,3)\}$, then $(2,3,3)U = \{(2,3,3,1,2),(2,3,3,2,1,3)\}$.
For notational convenience, we define $\emptyocc=\emptyocctuple$, and we use single boldface digits as abbreviations for singleton tuples, for example $\1=(1)$ and $\2=(2)$;
thus $u=(1,2)$ can be written more concisely as $u=\1\2$, and $w(2,2)u$ can be written more concisely as $w\2\2u$.

We say \emph{$u$ is within $w$}, written $u \occin w$,
iff $\exists q \in \mathbb{N}^{*}_{+} \suchthat u=wq$,
in which case we also define $u/w = q$.\footnote{This use of the operator $/$ allows
  a very pretty definition of the distributivity property for replacement in \cref{sec:replacement}.}
We say \emph{$u$ and $w$ are disjoint}, written $u \occdis w$, iff $\neg\bigl( u \occin w \logor w \occin u \bigr)$.
Finally, $u \occstrictin w$ means $u \occin w \logand u \neq w$,  $u \occcontains w$ means $w \occin u$,  $u \occstrictcontains w$ means $w \occstrictin u$, 
and $u \occdiseq w$ means $u \occdis w \logor u = w$.

For any term $M \in \termset$, we define its \emph{set of occurrences} $\occ(M) \subset \mathbb{N}_{+}^{*}$, as shown in \cref{fig:occurrences}, and the \emph{subterm of $M$ at $u$},
$M/u \in \termset$, where $u \in \occ(M)$, as shown in \cref{fig:selection}. We overload the relations $\occin$ and $\occstrictin$ to apply to terms:
$M \occin N$ means $\exists u \suchthat M = N/u$, 
and $M \occstrictin N$ means $\exists u \neq \emptyocc \suchthat M = N/u$.\footnote{Instead of using $\occin$ to compare occurrences,
  \citet[Section 3.1]{Huet80} defines the \emph{prefix ordering} relation $\preceq$
  on tuples: $w \preceq u$ iff $\exists q \in \mathbb{N}^{*}_{+} \suchthat u=wq$.
  The notion of occurrences unfortunately runs up against an irreconcilable conflict of terminology:
  the tuple representing occurrence $u$ is contained within the tuple representing occurrence $w$
  if and only if the subterm $M/w$ is contained within $M/u$---note the unfortunate chiasmus of $u$ and $w$.
  We have chosen a notation for comparing occurrences that emphasizes the relationships of subterms
  selected by occurrences rather than the relationships of the tuple representation of occurrences.
  This allows us to say that $M/u \occin M/w$ if and only if $u \occin w$.}
We also say that \emph{$u$ is an occurrence of the term $M/u$ in $M$}.

We define $\occ(M,N)$ (the \emph{occurrences of $M$ in $N$}) to mean $\setcomp{u}{u\in\occ(N) \logand N/u=M}$.  
We define $\uniqueocc(M,N)$ (the \emph{unique occurrence of $M$ in $N$}) to mean $u$ where $\occ(M,N) = \{u\}$;
$\uniqueocc(M,N)$ is undefined if $\left||\occ(M,N)\right|| \neq 1$.
\guy{Consider the notations $N/M$ and $!(N/M)$.}

